
Singleton Design Pattern ek creational pattern hai jo ensure karta hai ki:
poore application me kisi class ka sirf ek hi object banega, aur usko globally access kiya ja sakta hai.

“Singleton ek creational design pattern hai jo ensure karta hai ki kisi class ka sirf ek hi instance bane aur usko globally access kiya ja sake. Isme constructor private hota hai, ek static instance maintain kiya jata hai, aur ek public static method se usko access karte hain.”

One class → One object → Global access

Example real life:
Database connection (100 connection khol diye to system crash)
Logger (har jagah same logging instance use hota hai)

Flow (step-by-step logic)
Step 1: Constructor ko private bana do -> taaki koi bahar se new na kar sake
Step 2: Static variable banate hain -> yeh ek hi object hold karega
Step 3: Public method dete hain access ke liye

public static Singleton getInstance() {
    if(instance == null) {
        instance = new Singleton();
    }
    return instance;
}

Features
Single instance creation
Global access point
Controlled resource usage
Lazy loading possible
Thread-safe version possible

Advantages
Memory efficient (multiple object nahi ban rahe)
✔ Global access (kahin se bhi use kar sakte ho)
✔ Resource control (DB, logging, config)
✔ Lazy initialization possible

Disadvantages (ye bolna = strong candidate)
❌ Global state bana deta hai (bad practice ho sakti hai)
❌ Testing difficult ho jata hai (mocking issue)
❌ Multi-threading me dikkat (agar handle na karo)
❌ Overuse = tight coupling


Types (interviewer ko impress karne ke liye)
1. Eager Initialization = object pehle hi ban jata hai
2. Lazy Initialization = jab first time call hota hai tab banega
3. Thread-Safe Singleton
4. Double-Checked Locking (pro level)

Real-world Use Cases
Database connection pool
Logger
Configuration manager
Cache manager